<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="default.xsl"?><fr:tree xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml" toc="true" numbered="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="true" root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1195</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>def-0027</fr:addr><fr:route>def-0027.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Polynomial</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    A function <fr:tex>f: R  \to  R</fr:tex> is a <fr:strong>polynomial</fr:strong> with coefficients in ring <fr:tex>R</fr:tex> if
    there exists  <fr:tex>n  \in   \N</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>a_0, a_1,  \ldots , a_n  \in  R</fr:tex> such that
    <fr:tex display="block">         f(x) = a_0 + a_1 x + a_2 x^2 +  \cdots  + a_n x^n     </fr:tex>
    for all <fr:tex>x  \in  R</fr:tex>. We denote the set all polynomials with coefficients in <fr:tex>R</fr:tex> by <fr:tex>\mathcal {P}(R)</fr:tex>.
</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:contributions></fr:contributions><fr:context></fr:context><fr:related></fr:related><fr:backlinks><fr:tree xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml" toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="true" root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1192</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>def-0026</fr:addr><fr:route>def-0026.xml</fr:route><fr:title><fr:tex>\mathcal {P}_m (R)</fr:tex></fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    The set of all polynomials of degree at most <fr:tex>m</fr:tex> with coefficients in ring <fr:tex>R</fr:tex> is denoted by <fr:tex>\mathcal {P}_m (R)</fr:tex>.
    In other words,
    <fr:tex display="block">          \mathcal {P}_m (R) =  \set { p  \in   \mathcal {P}(R) |  \deg (p)  \leq  m}     </fr:tex>
    where <fr:tex>\mathcal {P}(R)</fr:tex> is the <fr:link href="def-0027.xml" type="local" addr="def-0027">set of all polynomials</fr:link> with coefficients in <fr:tex>R</fr:tex>.
</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml" toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="true" root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1193</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>def-0028</fr:addr><fr:route>def-0028.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Degree of polynomial</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    A <fr:link href="def-0027.xml" type="local" addr="def-0027">polynomial</fr:link> <fr:tex>p \in   \mathcal {P}(R)</fr:tex> is said to have degree <fr:tex>n</fr:tex> if
    there exists coefficients <fr:tex>a_0, a_1,  \ldots , a_n  \in  R</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>a_n  \neq  0</fr:tex> such that
    <fr:tex display="block">         p(x) = a_0 + a_1 x + a_2 x^2 +  \cdots  + a_n x^n     </fr:tex>
    for all <fr:tex>x  \in  R</fr:tex>. We denote the degree of <fr:tex>p</fr:tex> by <fr:tex>\deg (p) = n</fr:tex>.
    For the zero polynomial, we define its degree to be <fr:tex>- \infty</fr:tex>.
</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml" toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="true" root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1194</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:addr>eg-0002</fr:addr><fr:route>eg-0002.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Differentiation is linear map</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    Define <fr:tex>D \in \mathcal {L} ( \mathcal {P}( \mathbb {R} ), \mathcal {P}( \mathbb {R} ))</fr:tex> (recall that <fr:tex>\mathcal {P}</fr:tex> means <fr:link href="def-0027.xml" type="local" addr="def-0027">set of polynomials</fr:link>) by
    <fr:tex display="block">         D(f) = f&apos;     </fr:tex>
    We can see that <fr:tex>D</fr:tex> a linear map.
    <fr:ul><fr:li>Additivity: <fr:tex>D(f+g) = (f+g)&apos; = f&apos; + g&apos; = D(f) + D(g)</fr:tex></fr:li>
        <fr:li>Homogeneity: <fr:tex>D( \alpha  f) = ( \alpha  f)&apos; =  \alpha  f&apos; =  \alpha  D(f)</fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul></fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:backlinks><fr:references></fr:references></fr:backmatter></fr:tree>